### Step 2: Modify `storyService.js` -- Add Non-Blocking Embedding Generation

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\services\storyService.js`

#### 2a. Add import

At the top of the file, add:

```js
import GenerateEmbeddings from "../utils/GenerateEmbeddings.js";
```

#### 2b. Create a helper function for fire-and-forget embedding updates

Add a new private helper function after the existing `fetchAuthorProfiles` function (after line 24):

```js
/**
 * Generate an embedding from title + description and persist it to the story row.
 * This is intentionally fire-and-forget: failures are logged but never propagate.
 */
const updateStoryEmbedding = async (storyId, title, description) => {
    try {
        const embedding = await GenerateEmbeddings(title || '', description || '');

        if (!Array.isArray(embedding) || embedding.length === 0) {
            console.warn(`story embedding: empty result for story ${storyId}, skipping`);
            return;
        }

        const { error } = await supabase
            .from('stories')
            .update({ embedding })
            .eq('id', storyId);

        if (error) {
            console.warn(`story embedding: failed to save for story ${storyId}:`, error.message);
        }
    } catch (err) {
        console.warn(`story embedding: generation failed for story ${storyId}:`, err?.message || err);
    }
};
```

**Why a separate update instead of including in the insert?** The requirement says embedding failure must not block story creation. The cleanest way to achieve this is:
1. Insert/update the story as it works today (no embedding in the payload).
2. After the successful insert/update, fire off the embedding generation + update asynchronously.
3. The `.catch()` on the promise ensures the caller never awaits or sees the error.

#### 2c. Modify `createStoryService` (line 26)

After the successful insert (after line 80, just before `return data;`), add the fire-and-forget call:

```js
    // Non-blocking: generate and store embedding
    updateStoryEmbedding(data.id, data.title, data.description).catch(err =>
        console.warn('non-fatal: story embedding on create failed:', err?.message || err)
    );

    return data;
```

The `.catch()` ensures that even if the promise rejection is unhandled, it logs and does not crash the process.

#### 2d. Modify `updateStoryService` (line 215)

After the successful update (after line 282, just before `return data;`), add the fire-and-forget call. We only regenerate the embedding if `title` or `description` actually changed:

```js
    // Non-blocking: regenerate embedding if title or description changed
    if (updates.title !== undefined || updates.description !== undefined) {
        updateStoryEmbedding(data.id, data.title, data.description).catch(err =>
            console.warn('non-fatal: story embedding on update failed:', err?.message || err)
        );
    }

    return data;
```

This is efficient -- if the user only changes `status`, `privacy`, `tags`, or `cover_url`, the embedding is not regenerated since those fields do not affect semantic content.

